{#overview}
:::
InteropButton styles are driven purely by Interop\'s bundled CSS.
Use our prerolls (and roll your own) with no imports (not even InteropButton) and no associated bundle cost.
:::
{#sizes}
:::
Interop ships five button sizes: `xs`, `sm`, `md`, `lg`, `xl`.

Why would you want an extra-small and an extra-large button? I don't know. I'm not a good guesser.
The extra small button only provides a vertical click height of ~25px.
Even assuming a fine pointer context, that's too small for anyone's comfort. I'd skip it entirely.



(default, *action-minus*, *action*, *action-plus*) plus a *colorway* variant.
Drop the size onto `interop-button="<size>"` and the variant onto
`interop-button="<variant> <size>"`.
Interop provides a straightforward token system for creating buttons that feel right at home in your design. The default button styles shown here can be used as is or as models for your own exploration.
Every Interop button is built atop the same chassis.
This means that any button can be transformed into any other Interop button simply by changing the string values in the `interop-button`  attribute.
:::

{#disabled}
:::
Setting `[disabled]="true"` blocks pointer and keyboard activation, applies
the standard disabled styling, and ensures assistive tech announces the
button as unavailable. No additional ARIA wiring needed.
:::

{#loading}
:::
`[loading]="true"` swaps the label for an indeterminate spinner and prevents
activation while in flight. The button keeps its width so surrounding layout
doesn't shift when the state toggles.
:::

{#throttle}
:::
The handler fires *immediately* on the leading edge, then ignores further
activations for the configured window. Use this when the action represents a
discrete burst — a click that should never be missed, but also never doubled.
:::

{#debounce}
:::
Activation is *deferred* until the user stops clicking. Each new click resets
the timer. Best for search-as-you-type or any handler whose work is wasted if
another click is on its way.
:::

{#reentrancy}
:::
With `reentrant: false`, a second click while the handler is still running is
silently dropped. Pair this with async handlers (network, file IO) where a
double-submit would be a correctness bug, not just a UX annoyance.
:::

{#playground}
:::
With `reentrant: false`, a second click while the handler is still running is
silently dropped. Pair this with async handlers (network, file IO) where a
double-submit would be a correctness bug, not just a UX annoyance.
:::
